<h2>Arbitration Retainer Letter - Dennis Spencer Kahane</h2>
<PRE>
Contributor: Dennis Spencer Kahane

Address: 3130 Crow Canyon Place #270
San Ramon, California 94583

Telephone: (510) 901-1100
Fax: (510) 901-1104
BBS: (510) 901-1110
Primary Internet Address: <a href=mailto:kahane@kahane.com>kahane@kahane.com</a>
Website: <a href=http://www.kahane.com>www.kahane.com</a>


 Arbitration retainer letter

    The  Law Offices of Dennis Spencer Kahane is available for the
private arbitration of business disputes. Arbitration is to be
conducted pursuant to the California Arbitration Act. All parties
must be represented by separate counsel.
    An Arbitration Agreement must be entered into:

1. Specifying the nature of the dispute;

2. Specifying the scope and extent of the issues to be arbitrated;


3. Specifying the procedure of the arbitration:
 
   a. written submission only (Opening Brief; Reply Brief;
Supporting Declarations and documentary evidence under affidavit);
   b. live testimony (direct and cross examination) and
identification of evidence;
   c. full trial (Opening and Closing Argument; live testimony;
Trial Brief)

4. Specifying the applicability or non-applicability of the rules
of evidence and the rules of civil procedure;

5. Specifying the arbitrator's powers and the acceptance and
enforceability of his Decision and Award;

6. Specifying the extent of the Decision sought by the parties:
  a. one-liner: who's won; how much?
  b. Findings of Fact; Conclusions; Award.
  c. Full legal decision; facts; reasoning; legal precedents based
 on arbitrator's independent research, aided by the parties' briefs.

7. Specifying whether the arbitrator's Decision shall be final
and unappeasable, even if a party believes it to be incorrect or
believes the arbitrator has failed to understand the facts or his
misread, misconstrued or misapplied the law. An agreement
respecting the finality of the arbitrator's decision will not
prohibit any party from filing a petition to correct or vacate the
Decision pursuant to the Arbitration Act, nor will it prevent any
party from requesting Reconsideration by the arbitrator pursuant
to the Arbitration Act.

 8. Specifying that each party will pay its proportional share of
the arbitrator's fees (two parties, each pays one- half), subject
to (or not subject to) reapportionment in favor of the prevailing
party. Fees are figured at the usual hourly rates of the Law
Offices of Dennis Spencer Kahane, plus costs, as set forth in the
firm's Fee Schedule. A retainer of $5,000 is required ($2,500 from
each party, if two parties). The retainer must be replenished to
the $5,000 level upon billing. No work will be undertaken without
the appropriate retainer in the account. No decision will be
rendered without the retainer at the specified level.
   At the conclusion of the arbitration (after the time for
reconsideration has passed), any funds left on account will be
disbursed to the parties in accordance with their percentage of
contribution, and without regard to any provision awarding costs
to the prevailing party. No party may defeat the arbitration by
failing to pay or to replenish the retainer. The parties must
agree (and so state in the Arbitration Agreement or by separate
subsequent agreement) that the failure of any party to pay timely
into the retainer account such amounts as are required shall
result in a default Decision and Award against such party.

There may be no ex-parte telephone calls to the arbitrator: all
communication shall be by
  (a) mail, courier, or facsimile telecopier (fax) with a copy
sent by the same mode to the opposing party or parties, or
  (b) by pre-arranged all-party conference either (i) in person or
(ii) by telephone. Conferences may be either attorneys-only or
attorneys and clients, as the arbitrator may decide upon request
of counsel.  The scheduling of conferences, etc., may be discussed
by telephone with the arbitrator's secretary.

The parties are encouraged to make their Arbitration Agreement as
thorough as possible. In a private arbitration the precise terms,
constraints, limitations on damages, and scope, as set forth in
the Arbitration Agreement, govern the arbitration proceeding and
the Decision and Award. the Law Offices of Dennis Spencer Kahane,
the parties agree that general principals respecting judicial
immunity shall apply to the arbitrator as well as such immunities
from liability as are provided in the Arbitration Act.

Finally, arbitration is NOT mediation. The arbitrator will NOT
attempt to settle any matter submitted. The parties are encouraged
to settle a matter during the pendency of the arbitration
proceeding if they so choose, but the arbitrator will not play a
role in such settlement. The arbitrator does not view his role in
resolving disputes as (in the Solomonic phrase) "cutting the baby
in half," i.e., deciding issue 1 for Party A and issue 2 for Party
B, unless such course is dictated by the facts and law. Issues
will be decided according to their merits, as the arbitrator sees
them and without any attempt to "balance" the Decision and Award.
Parties who seek a balanced result are advised to settle.

As a preliminary step toward retaining the Law Offices of Dennis
Spencer Kahane for arbitration, counsel are requested to forward
information so that any conflicts may be identified.

 The Law Offices of Dennis Spencer Kahane will not serve as an
arbitrator in any dispute where any one of the parties has a
pre-existing relationship with Dennis Kahane, either socially,
familiarly, or professionally as a client, unless upon full
disclosure a written waiver of conflict is signed by all parties.

For additional information, contact:

Law Offices of Dennis Spencer Kahane
3130 Crow Canyon Place
Suite 270
San Ramon, CA 94583
USA
(510)-901-1100 (Voice)
(510)-901-1110 (BBS)
</PRE>
