<h2>Model Employee Handbook Outline - Snell & Wilmer</h2>

<pre>
Contributor: Gerald Morales

Firm: Snell & Wilmer

Address: One Arizona Center

Phoenix, Arizona 85004-0001

Telephone: (602) 382-6362

Fax: (602) 382-6070

E-mail: <a href="mailto:jmorales@counsel.com">jmorales@counsel.com</a>

Model Employee Handbook Outline*
Copyright 1995 by Gerard Morales

Note: Items listed with (e) should be considered essential

I. Introductory
A.  Welcome to Organization

(e) B.  Scope of Handbook (what it is)

(e) C.  Conspicuous Disclaimer (what it is not) employment at will
explanation of probation (if any) (e)  D. Code of Ethics
commitment to compliance with statutory requirements (not intended
to extend statute of limitations) expectation of employees
(monitoring and reporting) prohibition of retaliation

E. Definition of Terms

II. Policies and Procedures

(e)  A. Discipline
compliance as minimum requirement: not equal to adequate
performance compliance does not affect at-will relationship
possible sanctions: termination, demotion, transfer, suspension,
reprimand, counseling, etc. (not progressive: depends solely on
employer's view of what is appropriate)

(e)  B.  Prohibition of Harassment

C. General Conduct and Attire
attendance and promptness
attention to duties
compliance with policies and procedures
compliance with supervisory authority
dress code
illegal or unethical conduct
courtesy
gossip and rumors
care of property; avoidance of waste
responsibility for visitors
teamwork
conflict with coworkers

D.  Employment of Family Members

(e) E.  Conflicts of Interest
self-dealing
transactions with family and friends

F.  Confidential Information
requests for employment information
client lists, confidential processes, etc. employee files:
personnel and medical

G.  Outside Employment

H.  Reimbursement of Expenses
use of personal vehicles
-  insurance coverage required
-  certification of insurance by agent

(e) I.  Solicitation and Distribution

J.  Substance Abuse

K.  Smoke-Free Environment

L.  Workplace Safety

M.  Open Door Policy

(e) N.  Reporting of Unusual Circumstances suspected violations of
law serious misconduct traffic accidents workplace hazards

(e) O.  Resolution of Disputes
(refer to separate ADR policy)

P.  Procedures for Termination of Employment by employee by
employer

III.  Employee Benefits
A.  Wages and Salary
FLSA description
time-keeping
requirements for overtime authorization

B.  Time Away from Work
holidays
personal leave
-  paid vacation
-  jury duty
-  military leave
-  educational leave
-  unpaid personal leave
illness leave
-  paid sick leave
-  paid disability leave
-  workers' compensation (describe law)
-  extended medical leave (FMLA description) -  bereavement leave

C.  Welfare Plans (for information regarding any of the following
types of plans that may be offered, employees should be referred
to the most recent of the official plan summaries distributed from
time to time) pension deferred compensation or other savings
incentive stock purchase severance payments medical insurance life
insurance

IV.  Employee Relations Programs
A.  Credit Union
B.  Educational Assistance
C.  Employee Discounts
D.  Service Awards
E.  Company-Sponsored Activities

V.  Separate Employee Waivers and Agreements
A.  Alternative Dispute Resolution
B.  Employee Consent to Drug Testing new applicants present employees
</pre>

