<H2>Sexual Harassment Policy - University of San Francisco</H2>

<P>Contributor: Robert Curran, S.J.<BR>
Source: University of San Francisco<BR>
Firm: Office of the University Counsel<BR>
Address: 2130 Fulton St., University Center, Room 410, San Francisco, CA 94117-1080<BR>
Telephone: (415) 666-6822<BR>
Fax: (415) 666-6501<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:rcurran0@counsel.com">rcurran0@counsel.com</A></P>

<H3>Policy on Sexual and Other Unlawful Harassment (Approved by The President's Cabinet May 1991)</H3>

<H3>A. POLICY ISSUES</H3>

<H4>1. Purpose</H4>

<P>The purpose of this policy is to state clearly and unequivocally that the University prohibits sexual, racial and other forms of unlawful harassment by its faculty, staff and students. The University of San Francisco is committed to providing faculty, staff and students a work and academic environment free of sexual and other unlawful harassment. The University maintains a strict policy prohibiting harassment on the basis of sex, race, religion, color, national origin, disability, medical condition (cancer- related), marital status, age, sexual orientation, or any other basis protected by federal, state or local ordinance or regulation.  All such harassment is unlawful.</P>

<H4>2. Policy</H4>

<P>It is the policy of the University that sexual and other unlawful harassment will not be tolerated.  In addition, false accusations of such harassment will not be tolerated.  It is the policy of the University to (1) provide a harassment complaint procedure to review and act upon complaints of unlawful harassment; (2) thoroughly investigate in a timely manner complaints of unlawful harassment; (3) protect the rights and confidentiality of all parties to the harassment allegations to the extent possible; and (4) prevent retaliation against persons alleging sexual and other unlawful harassment or persons cooperating in an investigation. It is the intention of the University to take whatever action may be needed to prevent, correct, and, if necessary, discipline to the extent of dismissal from University employment or expulsion from the University, behavior which violates this policy. Wherever an instance of unlawful harassment, knowingly false accusation, reprisal for reporting or threatening to report unlawful harassment has been documented by evidence, appropriate disciplinary action up to and including dismissal or expulsion from the University will be taken consistent with applicable federal, state and local laws, University employment and academic policies, and collective bargaining agreements.</P>

<H4>3. Application</H4>

<P>This policy applies to University faculty, staff and students involved in any employment and/or academic relationship at the University.  Employees covered by collective bargaining agreements are subject to their own policies and procedures related to sexual and other unlawful harassment because of collective bargaining agreements.</P>

<H4>4. Definitions</H4>

<H4>A. Sexual Harassment</H4>

<P>Sexual harassment is defined as unwelcome sexual advances, requests for sexual favors, and other verbal or physical conduct of a sexual nature when: 1. Submission to such conduct is made either explicitly or implicitly a term or condition of an individual's employment or status in a program, course, or activity; or 2. submission to or rejection of such conduct by an individual is used as the basis for employment or educational decisions affecting an individual; or  3. such conduct has the purpose or effect of unreasonably interfering with an individual's work or educational performance, or creating an intimidating, hostile or offensive work or educational environment.</P>

<P>Examples:</P>

<P>Verbal conduct such as epithets, derogatory comments, slurs or unwanted or unwelcome sexual advances, invitations or comments. Visual conduct such as derogatory or sexually explicit posters, photography, cartoons, drawings or gestures. Physical conduct such as unwanted or unwelcome touching, blocking normal movement or interfering with work directed at the individual because of his or her sex or race or any other protected basis. Threats and demands to submit to sexual requests in order to keep an individual's job or receive a grade and offers of job or educational benefits in return for sexual favors. Two types of sexual and other unlawful harassment exist: Quid pro quo cases are those cases in which the employee or student suffers or reasonably believes he/she will suffer a tangible job or educational detriment in retaliation for refusing to accede to sexual demands. Hostile environment cases are those cases in which no tangible loss or detriment occurs, but an offensive or abusive atmosphere is created by the harasser.</P>

<H4>B. Other Unlawful Harassment</H4>

<P>Unlawful harassment consists of unwelcome statements or actions that are sufficiently severe or pervasive so as to interfere with an individual's work performance or create an intimidating, hostile or offensive work or academic environment based on sex, race, religion, color, national origin, disability, medical condition(cancer-related), marital status, age, sexual orientation, or other protected group status.</P>

<H4>5. Retaliation Prohibited</H4>

<P>Retaliation by anyone in the University Community against a member of the University Community as a result of his or her seeking redress under this policy, (e.g. informal or formal complaints about harassment, cooperating in an investigation, or otherwise participating in proceedings under this policy) is prohibited and may result in disciplinary action up to and including discharge from University employment/dismissal or expulsion from the University.</P>

<H4>6. Confidentiality</H4>

<P>Every reasonable effort shall be made to protect the privacy of the complainant and the alleged harasser in the investigation and resolution process, subject to the need to conduct a full and impartial investigation, remedy violations, monitor compliance and administer this policy.</P>

<H3>B. PROCEDURAL GUIDELINES FOR ADDRESSING COMPLAINTS OF  SEXUAL AND OTHER UNLAWFUL HARASSMENT</H3>

<P>The University has established a sexual and other unlawful harassment complaint procedure to encourage employees and students covered by this policy to seek redress for sexual or other unlawful harassment. This procedure applies to all complaints of sexual or other unlawful harassment. Informal Complaint Procedure The complainant has up to 180 days after the alleged incident(s) to make a complaint.</P>

<P>A. Faculty, staff or students who believe they have been unlawfully harassed in ways prohibited by this policy shall contact one of the following intake offices where someone is designated to receive such complaints: 1)  Counseling Center, ext. 6352 2)  Campus Ministry, ext. 6582 3)  Affirmative Action Officer, Personnel Services, ext. 6707  4)  Residence Life, ext. 6824</P>

<P>B. During the intake the complainant will be made aware of a range of options, which include the following: 1) the complainant may meet informally with the complainant's appropriate Dean, Director or Supervisor in an attempt to resolve the matter informally, or 2) the complainant may choose to discuss the complaint with the person accused, with the option of having the intake person present, or 3) at the request of the complainant the intake person may choose to discuss the complaint with the accused, or 4) the complainant may file a formal complaint.</P>

<P>C. If the alleged problem cannot be resolved informally within 10 working days after notification of the complaint, the complainant may file a formal complaint with the intake office. The intake office will forward the complaint to the Assistant Vice President, Personnel Services.</P>

<H4>Formal Complaint Procedure</H4>

<P>If a complainant chooses to forego the informal procedures outlined under B.B.1-3, he/she may file a written formal complaint with the Assistant Vice President, Personnel Services. A formal complaint is based on an allegation that either quid pro quo or hostile environment sexual or other unlawful harassment has occurred.</P>

<P>A. Complainant's formal complaint of unlawful harassment must be submitted in writing to the Assistant Vice President, Personnel Services within 190 days of the alleged incident of harassment.  A notice that a complaint has been received will be given to the appropriate Dean, Director or Supervisor and the Vice President for the division of the accused.  A copy of the complaint will be given to the accused.</P>

<P>B. Following filing of a formal complaint, a formal investigation will begin. The Assistant Vice President of Personnel Services will select an impartial investigator from among three trained personnel, including the Affirmative Action Officer.  The investigators shall disclose any real or apparent conflict of interest or biases related to the parties to the Assistant Vice President for Personnel Services.</P>

<P>C. To the extent possible, the proceedings will be conducted to protect the confidentiality interests of both parties and afford the accused a full opportunity to respond to the allegations.</P>

<P>D. Within 60 working days of the filing of a formal complaint the Investigator will issue findings and a recommendation to the Dean, Director or Supervisor of the accused, for a decision. The recommendation may be disciplinary or discharge action.</P>

<P>E. The parties will be informed promptly by the appropriate Dean, Director, Supervisor or Vice President about the outcome of the proceedings in writing.</P>

<P>F. If the decision is unacceptable to the accused or complainant each may appeal.</P>

<H3>C. APPEAL</H3>

<H4>Step One</H4>

<P>If the decision is unacceptable, the accused or complainant may appeal.  The complainant or the accused may within 10 working days following receipt of notice of the decision submit a written appeal for a review to the Assistant Vice President for Personnel Services. The Assistant Vice President for Personnel Services shall within 10 working days following the appeal request, schedule and convene a meeting with a 'University Appeal Panel.</P>

<H4>Step Two</H4>

<P>The Panel shall be composed of three University administrators who have been trained in applicable laws and University procedures.  The Panel shall be selected by the Assistant Vice President for Personnel Services.  The three member Panel shall be from outside the Division where the complaint was filed.  Each party is limited to two objections either to an original member or a replacement. The Panel shall be empowered to (1) gather evidence and take whatever steps deemed necessary and appropriate to assure that all facts have been fully investigated, presented and considered as provided in the University Procedures Handbook; (2) determine the participants whom they will invite to the review meetings; (3) provide the participants with an opportunity to present evidence and information and to comment on evidence and information presented by others and (4) issue written findings of fact and recommendations for resolution. Panel recommendations for resolution shall either sustain, overturn or modify the results of the investigation. Having been given sufficient notice of date, time and location of the meeting, the accused and complainant shall be present during the review meeting or meetings.  The accused and complainant may be self-represented or be represented by one other person of his/her choice.  If the person does not attend the Panel meeting, the Panel will continue the meeting except for good cause.  The Panel meetings shall be confidential and not open to the public.  The Panel proceedings will be recorded.  A copy of the recording will be retained by Personnel Services.</P>

<H4>Step Three</H4>

<P>The Panel will review the complaint and shall issue written findings of fact and recommendations for resolution to the appropriate Vice President of the division within which the complaint is made within 30 working days following the conclusion of the review meeting or meetings.</P>

<H4>Step Four</H4>

<P>The appropriate Vice President shall review the Panel's report and within 15 working days following his/her review shall either accept, reject or modify the Panel's report. The decision of the Vice President shall be final and binding on all parties to the complaint. The appropriate Vice President's decision shall be in writing and shall be submitted to the Assistant Vice President for Personnel Services.; the Dean, Director or Supervisor of the accused; and the complainant and the accused. Time limits imposed in this policy may be altered for good cause and shall not affect jurisdiction to take any action. The foregoing review procedure supersedes each and every policy, understanding or agreement (whether written or oral) which may exist that pertains to the subject matter of the review procedure.</P>

