<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Legal Helpline Info</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/helpline.map/"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/helpline.gif" ALT="Legal Helpline" ISMAP BORDER="0"></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<H2>Legal Helpline Guidelines</H2>

<P>There are a few guidelines we ask you to follow in asking questions. These rules may sound strict, but they're for your protection and for the benefit of the online community. We want to make sure that using the Legal Helpline is a beneficial and valuable experience, that it doesn't in any way jeopardize any relationships you may create with a lawyer you hire to represent you, and that it gives useful information to others who will read your question and the resulting answer.</P>

<P>Questions must be general and must not include detailed facts about your specific case. We want everyone to learn from the inquiries sent to the Legal Helpline. Our panelists would not be able to answer a question about whether your neighbor can prove that the property line is three feet to the north or three feet to the south, for example. But they could explain how property line disputes with neighbors are generally resolved.</P>

<P>If you have any questions about how to phrase your question, please e-mail our Legal Helpline editor at <A HREF="mailto:legalhelp@counsel.com">legalhelp@counsel.com</A>. We'll work with you to help you to phrase your query so that it meets our editorial guidelines, and so that it will yield a response that will be helpful to all our users. If your question is inappropriately phrased, we may contact you for additional information.</P>

<P>Craig Matters<BR>
Editor<BR>
Court TV Law Center</P>

