<HtMl><head><title> Court TV Law Center Q & A</title></head><BODY BGCOLOR=ffffff VLINK=FF0005><P align=center><img width=400 height=60 src=/graphics/ctv/qanda/qanda3.gif></P><H3 align=center>Starting Your Own Business: Getting Funding</H3><P><OL><LI> <a href=#cash>How much cash do I need to have?</a><LI> <a href=#invest>I have a friend who wants to invest in my new business. What should I consider?</a><LI> <a href=#borrow>I need to borrow money. Where do I start?</a><LI> <a href=#write>Do I need to write a business plan?</a></ol></P><a name=cash><P></a><h3>1. How much cash do I need to have?</h3><blockquote>That depends on the kind of business you're starting. Start-up capital for a consulting business you intend to run out of your home will require far less cash initially than opening a store or manufacturing a product.<P>As a rule of thumb, if you're starting a home-based business, you should have at least six months of working capital for the business plus at least six months of living expenses for yourself and your family. Other small businesses may require one to two years (or longer) before they reasonably can be expected to break even. <P>More start-up businesses fail for want of capital than for any other reason. You need to be realistic about what the business will need to get going and what sacrifices you are willing to make from a personal financial standpoint. Before you start your business, it is a very good idea to pay down (or off) as much personal household debt as you can, then put yourself on a budget and stick with it. <a name=invest></blockquote></a><h3>2. I have a friend who wants to invest in my new business. What should I consider?</h3><blockquote>First, you need to think about the role this friend wants to take in the business. Does she want to participate in the development of the business or is she a passive investor? Is he look for an income stream or is he willing to wait for long-term growth?<P>Whenever people deal with friends or family in this context, they tend to make certain assumptions about the reasons for such an investment and not ask necessary questions. You may believe that a family member just wants to help you out financially, while he or she envisions a more active role in the running of the enterprise. <P>You need to talk about these expectations up front -- <I>before</I> the investment is made -- and you must articulate your mutual understanding in writing. A formal agreement is very desirable in these situations and is absolutely essential if the investment is actually a loan. The writing serves to formalize the relationship as it affects the business. It sets up the boundaries, so to speak, and gives each of you a framework for going forward.<P>Another point your friendly investors should consider is that if down the line you need additional working capital from third parties, you and your investors will likely have to subordinate your respective financial interests in the business to those of the third party, or you may be required to guarantee financial obligations. If you expect to seek outside capital at some point, as either a loan or additional capital, you should get your friendly investors to agree ahead of time to subordinate their interests in such circumstances and assess their willingness to guarantee obligations.<a name=borrow></blockquote></a><h3>3. I need to borrow money. Where do I start?</h3><blockquote>You need to look at your own resources (and those of interested family and friends) before you apply for any loans. Any lender is going to look for a significant personal financial commitment on your part as an indication of your belief that the proposed business will be successful.<P>Next, you should spend some time with the bank officer at your bank. While many commercial banks do not lend money to start-up businesses, some have developed special small business lending programs. While you may not yet have the track record to qualify for such loans, it is important to start the relationship with your banker early and to understand the bank's lending criteria so you can put yourself in a position to qualify later on. Your banker may also be able to get you credit lines based on the strength of your personal assets, which may give you a relatively fast way of getting cash. <P>Your banker can also help you find alternate financing. The best way to find business financing -- like a good job -- is through networking. Talk with professionals who serve the small business community, such as small business accountants, lawyers, etc., to scout out possible financing sources. Talk with other business owners in your industry about how they got their financing. Do your homework. Go to your local library for information. Contact professional organizations in your industry for guidance. Try the Small Business Administration, but don't neglect state and local small enterprise support programs. Find out what's available and determine whether you qualify. <P>Because lenders have varying criteria for making a loan, you'll want to have several proposals or applications going at the same time. It will help you comparison shop and may give you some negotiating leverage, but most important it will keep you on track if one of your potential lenders falls by the wayside. Once you have your financing, continue to network in this area. If your business is successful, you may outgrow your current financing arrangement and need a larger, more flexible facility. <a name=write></blockquote></a><h3>4. Do I need to write a business plan?</h3><blockquote>Yes. Even if you can wholly self-finance your new business, you need to plan where you want to go and how you intend to get there. You need a marketing plan to keep you focused and a financial plan to keep you on track. An accounting professional can help you develop a plan and assist you in preparing the formal business plan that most third-party lenders will require. </P><P><B>Any answers posted are for your information only and are not intended toconstitute legal advice.</B></P></blockquote><P><a href=/legalhelp/qanda/mcmorries.html><B><I>Main Page</I></B></a><P><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/stroke.gif" HEIGHT=15 WIDTH=547><BR><A HREF="/map/bottom.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/bottom.gif" ISMAP ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM BORDER=0 WIDTH=533 HEIGHT=30></A><BR><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/rights.gif" ALT="Copyright 1995 by the Courtroom Television Network. All Rights Reserved. No parts of this site may be reproduced in any form without permission of Court TV. Disclaimer: Nothing in this site is intended to constitute legal advice"></P></BODY></HTML> 
