<HtMl><head><title> Court TV Law Center Q & A</title></head><BODY BGCOLOR=ffffff VLINK=FF0005><P align=center><img width=400 height=60 src=/graphics/ctv/qanda/qanda3.gif></P><H3 align=center>Starting Your Own Business: The Planning Process<BR></H3><P><OL><LI> <a href=#one> Should I form a corporation or a partnership?</a><LI> <a href=#two> What kinds of records will I need to keep?</a><LI> <a href=#three> How far ahead do I need to plan?</a><LI> <a href=#four> I know I'll need to hire people to help me. What do I need to think about now?</a></ol></P><a name=one><P></a><h3>1. Should I form a corporation or a partnership?</h3><blockquote>Deciding on the legal form for your new business venture is a highly individualized process. If you are on your own, your choices are generally either sole proprietorship or incorporation. If others are investing in the business, you can set up as a corporation, partnership, limited partnership, or limited liability company. [The <a href=/legalhelp/business/organization/>Court TV Legal Survival Guide</a> has good explanations of each of these forms.] Each form of ownership has pros and cons, as well as tax considerations that you will need to evaluate. I strongly suggest that you seek the advice of a good tax accountant and a lawyer to help you sort through the legal and tax implications of each. <a name=two></blockquote></a><h3>2. What kinds of records will I need to keep?</h3><blockquote>Recordkeeping is often neglected in the excitement of starting up a business, and thus it tends to get done haphazardly. If you think about recordkeeping before you start you business, you can save yourself untold hours of administrative time later on (when you can least afford the time). Much of your recordkeeping can be done on your personal computer. By thinking about the types of information you will want to manage and keep track of, you can select software packages that work well together. <P>Your accountant can help you set up your financial records so that pulling together your financial business plan won't seem like such a chore. On the non-financial end, the type of records you will need to maintain will depend on the type of business you are starting. It's probably a good idea to err on the side of overkill, at least in the beginning. Ask yourself this: If I were going to buy this business, what information would I want to see before I bought it to understand whether it's a good business? The answer should help you figure out the kind of information you're going to want to keep track of. <a name=three></blockquote></a><h3>3. How far ahead do I need to plan? </h3><blockquote>Again, the answer depends on what kind of business you're starting. Most established businesses use the budgeting process to develop their annual operating plans. These can be projected out three and five years, using assumptions about new products or services, expansion of markets, etc. (The further you go, however, the less reliable the plan becomes.) As a start-up, you should have a solid financial plan for at least a year or to your financial break-even point, whichever is longer. Beyond that, you should be thinking about where you want to go and developing a realistic approach for getting there. Putting such a plan in writing helps you stay on track.<a name=four></blockquote></a><h3>4. I know I'll need to hire people to help me. What do I need to think about now? </h3><blockquote>Whether and when to hire employees will again depend largely on the type of business you are starting. The old maxim  "staff for the lean times" is especially true for start-ups. It is far easier -- financially, emotionally and legally -- to hire people than to lay them off. In the beginning, you just don't know whether a flurry of activity is just that -- a flurry -- or a happy bellweather of things to come. <P>Many established businesses are rationalizing (i.e. reducing) their work forces and outsourcing the jobs they used to keep on the payroll. Using temporary workers or independent contractors initially can help you manage your overhead better and give you access to an experienced pool of workers. Over time, you can do the necessary financial figuring to see if hiring someone makes sense. </blockquote><P><a href=/legalhelp/qanda/mcmorries.html><B><I>Main Page</I></B></a><P><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/stroke.gif" HEIGHT=15 WIDTH=547><BR><A HREF="/map/bottom.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/bottom.gif" ISMAP ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM BORDER=0 WIDTH=533 HEIGHT=30></A><BR><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/rights.gif" ALT="Copyright 1995 by the Courtroom Television Network. All Rights Reserved. No parts of this site may be reproduced in any form without permission of Court TV. Disclaimer: Nothing in this site is intended to constitute legal advice"></P></BODY></HTML> 
