<HtMl><head><title> Court TV Law Center Q & A</title></head><BODY BGCOLOR=ffffff VLINK=FF0005><P align=center><img width=400 height=60 src=/graphics/ctv/qanda/qanda3.gif></P><H3 align=center>Starting Your Own Business: Protecting Yourself<BR></H3><P><OL><LI> <a href=#one>How do I make sure that no one steals my ideas?</a><LI> <a href=#two>I'm investing with my brother. What happens if we find we can't work together?</a><LI> <a href=#three>I'm hiring three people for my new business. Do I need to get them to sign anything when they start?</a><LI> <a href=#four>I have a logo and want to make sure that no one else will use it. What do I do?</a></ol></P><a name=one><P></a><h3>1. How do I make sure that no one steals my ideas?  </h3><blockquote>Virtually every business is going to have some type of unique information. Whether it is the kind of information that is legally protectable depends on a number of factors. For example, you may have a way of doing something or an invention that can only be commercially exploitable if potential users find out about it. Such information may be protectable under the U.S. copyright or patent laws. These laws protect your materials or inventions from being copied by others for a period of time. <P>There may be other things -- such as a formula or a processing method -- which you may not need to disclose to exploit commercially. Its value is in the fact that you possess the secret. Many states have what are known as trade secret laws, which protect such material under certain circumstances. And there are other materials that are not, strictly speaking, trade secrets, but nevertheless are things you want to keep confidential. <P>If proprietary information and ideas are a significant part of your new business, you should talk to a lawyer who is familiar with intellectual property and trade secret laws to help you take the necessary steps to protect this information.  <a name=two></blockquote></a><h3>2. I'm investing with my brother. What happens if we find we can't work together? </h3><blockquote>When going into business with other people, it's important to think about what could go wrong and have a plan for dealing with it. The best time to decide these points is before you get started. While it may seem odd to talk about and think about what will happen if your new venture goes sour, these type of discussions can help you and your partner or business associate articulate your respective expectations for the business. In fact, how these discussions go can give you a perspective on how well you will be able to work and communicate with one another. <P>But don't stop with discussions. Once you have both decided what will happen to the business if things don't work, you need to have an agreement that spells these points out. The form of this agreement will depend on the type of legal entity you decided to use. You should consult a lawyer for assistance, not just to memorialize your agreement, but to raise points that may not have occurred to you. <a name=three></blockquote></a><h3>3. I'm hiring three people for my new business. Do I need to get them to sign anything when they start? </h3><blockquote>Your new employees will need to complete a number of forms for the IRS. Aside from that, before you hire them, you should think about whether they'll have access to proprietary information. If they will, you may want them to sign confidentiality agreements to protect your trade secrets and other confidential information. Depending on their duties, the industry in which you are operating and other factors, you may want to have them execute an employment contract. [See our recent workshop <a href=/seminars/handbook/>The Ultimate Employee Handbook</a> for discussion of the pros and cons of employment contracts.]<P>If your business plan calls for hiring more than a few employees, you should consider preparing an employment policy and procedures manual, as well as instituting formal employment practices. While much of employment law is governed by federal law, a lot of the employer-employee relationship is governed by state law. You should consult an attorney familiar with these laws to help you design your policies and procedures. You will need specialized help to set up any benefit plans, such as health insurance, retirement plans, etc. <a name=four></blockquote></a><h3>4. I have a logo and want to make sure that no one else will use it. What do I do? </h3><blockquote>Logos and other identifying names for a product or service are covered by federal trademark laws. Strictly speaking, a trademark is a word used to identify a product produced by a specific maker, such as Kleenex (R) facial tissue or Xerox (R) copiers. A service mark does the same for a service, such as Century 21(R) Realtors. Symbols and logos may also be trademarks and service marks if they serve to identify the provider. The Rock of Gibraltar drawing used by Prudential Insurance is one example. <P>If you have an identifying mark for a product or service, you should consult with a trademark lawyer for help making the necessary filings with the U.S. Trademark Office to protect your mark.  </blockquote><P><a href=/legalhelp/qanda/mcmorries.html><B><I>Main Page</I></B></a><P><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/stroke.gif" HEIGHT=15 WIDTH=547><BR><A HREF="/map/bottom.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/bottom.gif" ISMAP ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM BORDER=0 WIDTH=533 HEIGHT=30></A><BR><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/rights.gif" ALT="Copyright 1995 by the Courtroom Television Network. All Rights Reserved. No parts of this site may be reproduced in any form without permission of Court TV. Disclaimer: Nothing in this site is intended to constitute legal advice"></P></BODY></HTML> 
