<HtMl><head><title> Court TV Law Center Q & A</title></head><BODY BGCOLOR=ffffff VLINK=FF0005><P align=center><img width=400 height=60 src=/graphics/ctv/qanda/qanda3.gif></P><H3 align=center>Starting Your Own Business: Selling Yourself and Your Services<BR></H3><P><OL><LI> <a href=#one>How much research should I do on my industry?</a><LI> <a href=#two>I think my business has the potential to be a nationwide success, but I don't want to bite off more than I can chew at first. How do I decide where and how to focus?</a><LI> <a href=#three>I am considering selling my product through independent sales representatives. What issues should I be concerned about? What kind of agreement do I need to draw up?</a><LI> <a href=#four>I am afraid that I will feel isolated once I go out on my own. What can I do to keep myself up to date?</a></ol></P><a name=one><P></a><h3>1. How much research should I do on my industry?</h3><blockquote>You should know as much about your industry as you can. The better informed you are about your industry, the better you'll be able to spot trends and capitalize on them. You will also understand who your competitors are -- both your real competitors and perceived competitors -- and will be able to distinguish yourself from them when it comes time to sell to a prospect. <P>Your research will also help you develop your business plan by injecting the necessary element of realism into the assumptions you include. Thorough knowledge of your industry will give you credibility with your prospective clients and customers, vendors, collateral businesses and, most important, the financial community.<P>Industry knowledge is the backbone of product or service development. Your new business should fill an identified need in your chosen market. You may have a "gut" feel for what is needed, but research can confirm this intuitive sense and help you refine the offering. <a name=two></blockquote></a><h3>2. I think my business has the potential to be a nationwide success, but I don't want to bite off more than I can chew at first. How do I decide where and how to focus? </h3><blockquote>Unless you are dealing with a "fad" product that requires mass market penetration quickly to capitalize on the fad, you should live by the story of the tortoise and the hare: Slow and steady wins the race. While widespread market acceptance can be exciting and gratifying, it can backfire if you are unable to meet customer demand for your product or service due to financial, facilities, manpower or capacity constraints. Where and how to focus your business should be the foundation of your business plan. <P>Established businesses spend a lot of resources on new product development and testing to give their product or service the best chance for widespread acceptance. Since you may not have the luxury of conducting significant test marketing, your best bet is to start with the markets that you know best. And don't just think in terms of geography. You can target a particular market segment or a particular distribution channel at the outset. Based on the reaction you get in these initial efforts, you can come up with an orderly, realistic plan for expansion.<a name=three></blockquote></a><h3>3. I am considering selling my product through independent sales representatives. What issues should I be concerned about? What kind of agreement do I need to draw up?</h3><blockquote>Independent sales representatives can be a cost-effective way of selling your product. Some rep groups are regional, others national. They are often confused with distributors. The difference usually is that a distributor buys your product and then sells it to the end user. A sales representative acts like a salesperson you have employed. Sales reps don't actually buy your product -- they act on your behalf to sell it to the end user. They are usually on commission. <P>You should research these groups before you contact them. If possible, talk to businesses that have used them to get a feel for how you think they may handle your product. You'll want to think about compensation and commission structure, sales targets, representing competing products, etc. Most rep groups have standard contracts they will want you to sign. You should have these reviewed by legal counsel and make changes that you feel will be in your best interest. <a name=four></blockquote></a><h3>4. I am afraid that I will feel isolated once I go out on my own. What can I do to keep myself up to date?</h3><blockquote>Stay active in any professional or trade groups are associated with your industry. Develop contacts at collateral businesses. Join any local small business forums or groups. Become active in the online community by reading and participating in online mailing lists, discussion groups, etc. In other words, network, network, network. It will help you stay in touch, keep up to date, spot trends, and sell yourself and your business. Good luck! </blockquote><P><a href=/legalhelp/qanda/mcmorries.html><B><I>Main Page</I></B></a><P><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/stroke.gif" HEIGHT=15 WIDTH=547><BR><A HREF="/map/bottom.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/bottom.gif" ISMAP ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM BORDER=0 WIDTH=533 HEIGHT=30></A><BR><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/rights.gif" ALT="Copyright 1995 by the Courtroom Television Network. All Rights Reserved. No parts of this site may be reproduced in any form without permission of Court TV. Disclaimer: Nothing in this site is intended to constitute legal advice"></P></BODY></HTML> 
