<HtMl><head><title> Court TV Law Center Q & A</title></head><BODY BGCOLOR=ffffff VLINK=FF0005><P align=center><img width=400 height=60 src=/graphics/ctv/qanda/qanda3.gif></P><H3 align=center> Using Mediation to Handle Your Divorce</H3><h3>1. What is Mediation?</h3><blockquote>In mediation a neutral third person helps people with a dispute resolvetheir differences. When the dispute is a legal controversy, the mediatoris often a lawyer, but one who is <I>strictly neutral</i>. Sherepresents neither party and is there solely to help resolve thecontroversy. She makes no decisions; rather, she helps the parties reachtheir own decisions. She is skilled at helping individuals carefullyconsider their goals, their interests, and their options. She helps themlisten to the other side's arguments and evaluate the strengths andweaknesses of their positions. She may also draft a formal statement ofany agreements.<p></blockquote></P><P><B><I>Any answers posted are for your information only and are not intended toconstitute legal advice.</I></B></P><P><a href=/legalhelp/qanda/james/index.html#tab><B><I>Main Page</I></B></a><P><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/stroke.gif" HEIGHT=15 WIDTH=547><BR><A HREF="/map/bottom.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/bottom.gif" ISMAP ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM BORDER=0 WIDTH=533 HEIGHT=30></A><BR><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/rights.gif" ALT="Copyright 1995 by the Courtroom Television Network. All Rights Reserved. No parts of this site may be reproduced in any form without permission of Court TV. Disclaimer: Nothing in this site is intended to constitute legal advice"></P></BODY></HTML> 
