<HtMl><head><title> Court TV Law Center Q & A</title></head><BODY BGCOLOR=ffffff VLINK=FF0005><P align=center><img width=400 height=60 src=/graphics/ctv/qanda/qanda3.gif></P><H3 align=center> Using Mediation to Handle Your Divorce</H3><h3>4. If we mediate our divorce, do we still have to have our own attorneys?</h3><blockquote>You don't need to "retain" an attorney -- that means paying a lot ofmoney for the lawyer to sign your pleadings [court papers] and, inessence, promise to represent you throughout the proceedings. But you<STRONG>do</strong> need to consult with a lawyer to be sure that youunderstand your legal rights and make informed decisions.<p>Remember, the mediator is neutral. She doesn't represent you or yourspouse. Because she's neutral, she cannot give you legal advice. She mayfeel comfortable sharing legal information with you -- such as childsupport guidelines, property rights in divorce, and other legal matters-- but she may not be comfortable suggesting how those laws apply toyour case. And she certainly won't want to recommend to you what youshould or shouldn't do.<p>A consulting attorney can sit down with you and make sure you know whatyou're doing. He can tell you how he thinks you would fare in court ifyou don't agree in mediation. He can advise you as to whether you shouldaccept an offer in mediation. He can review any paperwork the mediatordrafts to be sure your rights are protected. If your mediator doesn'twant to draft the legal papers, your lawyers may draft the formaldocuments.</blockquote></P><P><B><I>Any answers posted are for your information only and are not intended toconstitute legal advice.</I></B></P><P><a href=/legalhelp/qanda/james/index.html#tab><B><I>Main Page</I></B></a><P><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/stroke.gif" HEIGHT=15 WIDTH=547><BR><A HREF="/map/bottom.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/bottom.gif" ISMAP ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM BORDER=0 WIDTH=533 HEIGHT=30></A><BR><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/rights.gif" ALT="Copyright 1995 by the Courtroom Television Network. All Rights Reserved. No parts of this site may be reproduced in any form without permission of Court TV. Disclaimer: Nothing in this site is intended to constitute legal advice"></P></BODY></HTML> 
