<HtMl><head><title> Court TV Law Center Q & A</title></head><BODY BGCOLOR=ffffff VLINK=FF0005><P align=center><img width=400 height=60 src=/graphics/ctv/qanda/qanda3.gif></P><H3 align=center> Using Mediation to Handle Your Divorce</H3><h3>5. How much does it cost to mediate my divorce?</h3><blockquote>Your mediator will charge by the hour, so the cost depends on you. Howcomplicated are your legal issues and how agreeable are you? However, nomatter how complicated or contentious your divorce, it will almostcertainly be less expensive if you resolve your differences inmediation. It's far more efficient because you make decisions witheveryone sitting at the table together -- instead of through numerousattorney letters and phone calls. And because it's usually friendlier,you don't waste time and run up costs due to anger andmisunderstandings.<p>You'll also have the cost of your consulting attorney, but because youprobably won't need much of his time, that expense should be minor.<p></blockquote></P><P><B><I>Any answers posted are for your information only and are not intended toconstitute legal advice.</I></B></P><P><a href=/legalhelp/qanda/james/index.html#tab><B><I>Main Page</I></B></a><P><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/stroke.gif" HEIGHT=15 WIDTH=547><BR><A HREF="/map/bottom.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/bottom.gif" ISMAP ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM BORDER=0 WIDTH=533 HEIGHT=30></A><BR><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/rights.gif" ALT="Copyright 1995 by the Courtroom Television Network. All Rights Reserved. No parts of this site may be reproduced in any form without permission of Court TV. Disclaimer: Nothing in this site is intended to constitute legal advice"></P></BODY></HTML> 
