<HtMl><head><title> Court TV Law Center Q & A</title></head><BODY BGCOLOR=ffffff
VLINK=FF0005><P align=center><img width=400 height=60
src=/graphics/ctv/qanda/qanda3.gif></P>


<blockquote>

<H3>Ms. James Answers Your Questions</H3>

<P><font size=+2><B>Q:</B></font> What strategy do you suggest for the intransigent spouse who agrees to
mediate but still relishes playing games?</P>

<P><font size=+2><B>A:</B></font> Just get her/him to mediation. Let the mediator do her job. If the mediator
knows her craft, she'll discourage game-playing and get the two of you focused on
the real issues. Not many spouses continue to waste time and money on emotional
games when they're paying the mediator $200 an hour and that mediator is
reminding them of the legal issues that must be addressed.</P>





<p>
<I><B>If you think you need legal advice, you should <a
href=/legalhelp/business/lawyer/>consult a lawyer</a>.</B></I> </blockquote>
</p> </UL>



