<HtMl><head><title> Court TV Law Center Q & A</title></head><BODY BGCOLOR=ffffff VLINK=FF0005><P align=center><img width=400 height=60 src=/graphics/ctv/qanda/qanda3.gif alt="COURT TV LAW CENTER Q & A"></P><H3 align=center>Living Wills</H3><blockquote><font size=+2><B>Q:</B></font> If I were involved in a horrible car accident and wasn't able to make my own decisions, who would make them for me?<P><font size=+2><B>A:</B></font> It depends on several things: your age, where you live, where you have your accident, and what planning you have done beforehand.<p>At the scene of the accident and in the emergency room, the emergency personnel and doctors will make decisions for you. They have the authority and responsibility to stabilize you. In an emergency situation, the law presumes that the patient has given consent to whatever treatment is necessary to save his or her life. This means stopping bleeding, suturing wounds, giving transfusions, setting bones, doing CPR, etc.<p>If you are a minor, your parents have the legal authority to make decisions for you.<p>If you have prepared a living will -- a legal document that outlines what procedures you do and do not want performed for you in the event that you are incapacitated -- you will essentially be making decisions for yourself. In other words, your living will specifically tells the doctor which life-sustaining medical treatments you will or will not consent to if you are in the medical circumstances established by the state legislature.<p>If you have prepared a health care power of attorney, the person you name as your agent is the person the doctor will look to for medical decisions on your behalf.<p>If you have not prepared any medical treatment decision document, and your accident occurs in a state with a "family consent statute," the doctor will look for decisions from the person who has the highest priority among those listed in the statute. In most states, the priority list is first spouse, then adult children, then parents, then siblings, etc.<p>Outside of these circumstances, the answers get more fuzzy.<p><p></blockquote></P><P><B><I>Any answers posted are for your information only and are not intended toconstitute legal advice.</I></B></P><P><a href=/legalhelp/qanda/hurme/index.html#tab><B><I>Main Page</I></B></a><P><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/stroke.gif" HEIGHT=15 WIDTH=547><BR><A HREF="/map/bottom.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/bottom.gif" ISMAP ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM BORDER=0 WIDTH=533 HEIGHT=30></A><BR><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/rights.gif" ALT="Copyright 1995 by the Courtroom Television Network. All Rights Reserved. No parts of this site may be reproduced in any form without permission of Court TV. Disclaimer: Nothing in this site is intended to constitute legal advice"></P></BODY></HTML> 
