<HtMl><head><title> Court TV Law Center Q & A</title></head><BODY BGCOLOR=ffffff VLINK=FF0005><P align=center><img width=400 height=60 src=/graphics/ctv/qanda/qanda3.gif alt="COURT TV LAW CENTER Q & A"></P><H3 align=center>Living Wills</H3><blockquote><font size=+2><B>Q:</B></font> What are the limitations of a living will?<P><font size=+2><B>A:</B></font> The specific limitations of a living will depend on the state in which you live. In general, a living will is limited in the types of treatments that a person can direct the doctor to provide or withhold and the medical circumstances when the document comes into play. Most states restrict treatment to those procedures (defined in the statute) considered as life sustaining, including CPR and sometimes artificially administered hydration and nutrition. The states also restrict when the document is effective to "final days," which are defined differently in each state.</blockquote></P><P><B><I>Any answers posted are for your information only and are not intended toconstitute legal advice.</I></B></P><P><a href=/legalhelp/qanda/hurme/index.html#tab><B><I>Main Page</I></B></a><P><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/stroke.gif" HEIGHT=15 WIDTH=547><BR><A HREF="/map/bottom.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/bottom.gif" ISMAP ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM BORDER=0 WIDTH=533 HEIGHT=30></A><BR><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/rights.gif" ALT="Copyright 1995 by the Courtroom Television Network. All Rights Reserved. No parts of this site may be reproduced in any form without permission of Court TV. Disclaimer: Nothing in this site is intended to constitute legal advice"></P></BODY></HTML> 
