<HtMl><head><title> Court TV Law Center Q & A</title></head><BODY BGCOLOR=ffffff VLINK=FF0005><P align=center><img width=400 height=60 src=/graphics/ctv/qanda/qanda3.gif alt="COURT TV LAW CENTER Q & A"></P><H3 align=center>Living Wills</H3><blockquote><font size=+2><B>Q:</B></font> Does it make a difference if I designate my husband, my child, my parent or a friend as the person who will make my medical treatment decisions?<P><font size=+2><B>A:</B></font> Yes, but the difference depends on family dynamics and relationships, as well as trust, experience and availability. A husband may be a logical choice. But if he is out of the country on business, it's a bad choice. If you are on the verge of divorce, you might want to name someone else. You also should consider how others who could be named will go along with your choice of who you do name. To avoid potential conflicts at your bedside, talk to your loved ones now about your wishes and try to resolve any differences of opinion. If your family and friends know what your thoughts are, they will be in a better position to carry them out, rather than having to guess what you would want done.</blockquote></P><P><B><I>Any answers posted are for your information only and are not intended toconstitute legal advice.</I></B></P><P><a href=/legalhelp/qanda/hurme/index.html#tab><B><I>Main Page</I></B></a><P><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/stroke.gif" HEIGHT=15 WIDTH=547><BR><A HREF="/map/bottom.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/bottom.gif" ISMAP ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM BORDER=0 WIDTH=533 HEIGHT=30></A><BR><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/rights.gif" ALT="Copyright 1995 by the Courtroom Television Network. All Rights Reserved. No parts of this site may be reproduced in any form without permission of Court TV. Disclaimer: Nothing in this site is intended to constitute legal advice"></P></BODY></HTML> 
