<HtMl><head><title> Court TV Law Center Q & A</title></head><BODY BGCOLOR=ffffff VLINK=FF0005><P align=center><img width=400 height=60 src=/graphics/ctv/qanda/qanda3.gif alt="COURT TV LAW CENTER Q & A"></P><H3 align=center>Living Wills</H3><blockquote><font size=+2><B>Q:</B></font> Do my loved ones have any rights to make decisions for me?<P><font size=+2><B>A:</B></font> With a living will, your loved ones do not have any rights to make decisions for you. You have made the decisions and taken them out of the hands of your family. That's what the document is supposed to do -- you make the decision so your family doesn't have to. Even if your family disagrees with your decision, your living will should be controlling.<P>Without a living will, your loved ones have legal authority to make decisions for you depending onwhere they fall within the priority list in a "family consent" state. In actual practice, if thefamily members agree among themselves and the doctor agrees with the family, the family willparticipate in treatment decisions when there is no advance directive. When the family disagreesamong themselves or with the doctor, things get more complicated.</blockquote></P><P><B><I>Any answers posted are for your information only and are not intended toconstitute legal advice.</I></B></P><P><a href=/legalhelp/qanda/hurme/index.html#tab><B><I>Main Page</I></B></a><P><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/stroke.gif" HEIGHT=15 WIDTH=547><BR><A HREF="/map/bottom.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/bottom.gif" ISMAP ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM BORDER=0 WIDTH=533 HEIGHT=30></A><BR><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/rights.gif" ALT="Copyright 1995 by the Courtroom Television Network. All Rights Reserved. No parts of this site may be reproduced in any form without permission of Court TV. Disclaimer: Nothing in this site is intended to constitute legal advice"></P></BODY></HTML> 
