<HtMl><head><title> Court TV Law Center Q & A</title></head><BODY BGCOLOR=ffffff VLINK=FF0005><P align=center><img width=400 height=60 src=/graphics/ctv/qanda/qanda3.gif alt="COURT TV LAW CENTER Q & A"></P><H3 align=center>Living Wills</H3><blockquote><font size=+2><B>Q:</B></font> Where do I go to find out  more about living wills and my rights in this area?<P><font size=+2><B>A:</B></font> Talk to your doctor. Many hospitals have community education programs on advance directives, so you might call the social work or patient advocate  department. Area agencies on aging, state attorneys general, local bar associations and senior centers  all may have forms or programs on advance directives.<p>Legal Counsel for the Elderly, a department of AARP, has self-help guides to advance directives with living will and health care power of attorney forms for your state. The guides explain the law in your state, have ready-to-use forms and instructions, and discuss how to pick an agent, how to talk with your family and doctor. To order "Planning for  Incapacity" send $5 to Legal Counsel for the Elderly, P.O. Box 96474, Washington, DC 20090-6474.</blockquote></P><P><B><I>Any answers posted are for your information only and are not intended toconstitute legal advice.</I></B></P><P><a href=/legalhelp/qanda/hurme/index.html#tab><B><I>Main Page</I></B></a><P><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/stroke.gif" HEIGHT=15 WIDTH=547><BR><A HREF="/map/bottom.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/bottom.gif" ISMAP ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM BORDER=0 WIDTH=533 HEIGHT=30></A><BR><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/rights.gif" ALT="Copyright 1995 by the Courtroom Television Network. All Rights Reserved. No parts of this site may be reproduced in any form without permission of Court TV. Disclaimer: Nothing in this site is intended to constitute legal advice"></P></BODY></HTML> 
