<HtMl>
<head>
<title> Court TV Law Center Q & A</title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR=ffffff VLINK=FF0005>
<P align=center><img width=400 height=60 src=/graphics/ctv/qanda/qanda3.gif alt="COURT TV LAW CENTER Q & A"></P>

<H3 align=center>A Living Will Glossary</H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><B>Advance Directive:</B> A generic term for legal documents (such as a living will or health-care power of attorney) that states an individual's medical treatment preferences in the event he or she becomes unable to make his or her own decisions.

<P><B>Agent:</B> The person you choose to make decisions on your behalf if you become incapacitated. The agent is the person designated in a health-care power of attorney to act for the principal. This person may also be called the "surrogate."

<P><B>Cardiopulmonary Resuscitation (CPR): </B>Various medical technologies used to restore and maintain blood circulation and breathing in a person who has experienced cardiac and/or respiratory arrest.

<P><B>Coma:</B> A sleep-like (eyes closed) condition resulting from impairment of the brain stem. Often used to include all possible degrees of impaired consciousness or unresponsiveness with the absence of eye opening.

<P><B>Comfort Care:</B> Treatment or care which does not restore health but relieves pain, or eases (but not reverses) the dying process.

<P><B>Declaration:</B> A document which states an individual's views about the use of life-sustaining procedures when he or she is no longer able to make a health-care decision. The document is also called a "Living Will."

<P><B>Do-Not-Resuscitate (DNR) Order:</B> An order in a patient' s medical record to withhold cardiopulmonary resuscitation. Also called "no code."

<P><B>Durable Power Of Attorney For Health Care:</B> An advance directive that remains valid after the principal becomes incapacitated, and empowers a designated person (agent) to make health-care decisions for an incapacitated principal. Also known as a health care power of attorney.

<P><B>Execute:</B> Following the guidelines set down in the law for completing a document that is legally enforceable. This may include procedures such as having witnesses to your signature or signing in the presence of a notary public.

<P><B>HCPOA:</B> health-care power of attorney; also called a durable power of attorney for health care.

<P><B> Life-Sustaining Procedures:</B> Drugs, medical devices, or procedures that can keep individuals alive who would otherwise die within a short, though usually uncertain, time.

<P><B>Persistent Vegetative State (PVS):</B> A state of permanent unconsciousness that is irreversible. It may take one to six months or more to confirm a PVS diagnosis. Patients in PVS have had the centers in the brain that control thinking, speaking, hunger, and thirst destroyed. PVS patients do retain reflexes such as random eye or muscle movements, yawning and response to touch or sound. However, they do not feel pain. It includes patients with the appearance of wakefulness but excludes those who are more deeply comatose with eyes closed generally PVS is not considered a terminal condition, and a PVS patient may live for years with the assistance of medical equipment/treatment.

<P><B>Principal:</B> A person who signs a health care power of attorney granting an agent authority to act when he or she is unable to do so. The person must sign the HCPOA while capable of making his or her own health-care decisions

<P><B>Respirator:</B> Also called a ventilator, refers to a mechanical device that uses a tube through the nose or throat to assist breathing.

<P><B>Surrogate:</B> a person designated in a health-care power of attorney, a guardian appointed by the court, or any of the following in the indicated order of priority who are available wan willing to make a health-care decision:

<UL>
<LI> your spouse, unless you are legally separated;
<LI> your adult child (if more than one, a majority of those available);
<LI> your mother or father;
<LI> your domestic partner, unless someone else has financial responsibility; <LI> your brother or sister; or
<LI> a close friend of yours (someone who shows special concern for you and is familiar with you health-care views).</UL></P>

<P>This glossary was adopted from <I>Planning for Incapacity: A Self-Help Guide</I>, produced by Legal Counsel for the Elderly, a department of the American Association of Retired Persons.</BLOCKQUOTE>

