Rockingham gate, the gate is still open for the same length of time, 
regardless of when you parked. Correct? 
 
A: Correct. 
 
Q: Your state of mind at that time, Mr. Simpson, was that if you 
pulled out of the Rockingham gate and parked there, you were in a 
better position to get the dog? Is that what your saying? 
 
A: My state of mind at that time was to park the car and come back 
in, and I wasn't in the mood to go for Chachi, so I didn't want 
Chachi to go out of that gate. So that was my state of mind, yes. 
 
Q: But it was still possible for Chachi to leave the gate, though. 
 
A: No. Chachi is a relatively trained dog. If I'm there, she won't go 
out. If I say, "No, Chachi. Come here," she'll come here. 
 
Q: When you exit that gate to leave the property to go someplace 
else-- 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: --your dog can get out at any time. Correct? 
 
A: As I explained to you already, I thought in detail, normally I sit 
at the gate every morning when I go to play golf; I wait till the gate 
starts closing before I drive out of the gate every morning. 
 
Q: To make sure the dog doesn't leave. 
 
A: To make sure the dog doesn't leave. 
 
Q: You could have done so on this occasion. Correct? 
 
A: I didn't need to. 
 
Q: You could have exited, waited to see that the dog wasn't coming 
out. When the gate closed, you could have parked in your normal 
spot on Ashford. Correct? 
 
A: Why would I, since I wasn't going anywhere. So I could just 
step out of the car, which took me a matter of seconds, and say, 
"Come on Chachi. Don't go anywhere." 
 
Q: But you could have done so. Correct? 
 
MR. BAKER: It's physically possible. 
 
THE WITNESS: k would have been stupid to do so. 
 
