eventually to a split-up. 
But we didn't live anywhere else. I stayed at a friend's house for a 
few days. I spent the whole day at the house with her, but I just 
felt--I had some anger myself, and I just felt a little distance would 
help. So for about two days I stayed away, and I just hoped it 
wouldn't lead eventually--that this would be, as you call, a rift that 
wouldn't be something that could divide our relationship over a 
period of time, but at that particular time we did not split up. I 
believe we had friends over one week later, and we took a trip 
together within 30 days of this incident. 
 
Q: How much time went by after January 1, 1989 before Nicole 
and you reconciled? 
 
A: What do you mean by "reconciled?" You have to tell me what 
you mean by "reconciled." We never split. 
 
Q: What does "reconcile" mean to you? 
 
A: To me, to the--to me reconciled totally technically is if you split 
up, and then you reconcile when you come back together. 
 
Q: And that never happened. 
 
A: That never happened. 
 
Q: So you never split up, and therefore you never had to reconcile. 
Is that what you're saying? 
 
A: No. I think we had to reconcile what happened that night, for 
both of us. In that sense we needed a rec--- yeah, that's why we 
went to therapy. o We had to reconcile how did our relationship 
reach a point where something like this could happen. Yes. And I 
had to reconcile in my mind how I could let our relationship get to 
the point that I could be physical with her. It was--it was a 
traumatic thing for me. 
But as far as splitting up. she never called a lawyer. I never called a 
lawyer. It was not a situation like that. 
 
Q: What do you mean, she didn't call a lawyer? She prosecuted 
charges against you. 
 
A: No, she didn't. The D.A. did. 
 
Q: But she was the complaining party. Right? 
 
A: That night she was the complaining parry. 
 
Q: And she cooperated. Right? 
 
A: Of course she did.  
 
Q: And in fact you were convicted as a result of entering a plea of-- 
 
A: That's correct. 
 
Q:-of nolo contendere. 
 
A: That's correct. 
 
Q: You tried to talk her out of pursuing that, didn't you? 
 
A: We talked about that, yes. I asked her, 19 was she going to 
testify in court. She said no. 
 
Q: You were concerned about the damage it would do to your 
public image and your reputation. Correct? 
 
A: Partially, yes. 
 
Q: By the way, you went to therapy because the court ordered you 
to do so. Correct? 
 
A: That's absolutely wrong. 
 
Q: The court ordered you to go to therapy. Right? 
 
A: Six months later. I had been going to therapy for those five or 
six months. Whenever I got to court, I had started therapy 
immediately that week. 
 
Q: Your lawyer told you to do that. Right? 
 
A: No. I wanted to do that even before I saw my lawyer. My 
lawyer--I didn't see my lawyer or speak to my lawyer for a few 
days because he was out of town at that time. 
 
Q: But your lawyer advised you to do that 13 also. Right? 
 
MR. BAKER: Don't answer that, OJ. That's nonsense. 
 
