Q: --from Taft back to you, and you have the calendar in front of 
you. 
 
A: Yeah. 
 
Q: You see the 26th of May is Thursday. 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: What is your best recollection or when you initially dictated the 
letter? 
 
A: Right in there, right in this week somewhere (Indicating). 
 
Q: From the 23rd, 24th or 25th? 
 
A: Yes. It wasn't until after I got back from--it was this weekend, I 
think, that Nicole gave I Gigi the hard time. 
 
Q: 22nd and 23rd? 
 
A: 21st and 22nd. I think that's the weekend she gave Gigi the hard 
time. So it would have been this week that I would have dictated 
the letter (Indicating). 
 
Q: You are pointing to the week of May 23. 
 
A: Yeah.  Yeah. 
 
Q: Can you remember anything in that letter that you edited out? 
 
A: Not particularly. I just thought it was long, and I didn't like the 
way it sounded. To me it sounded sorta harsh. 
 
Q: Can you remember anything that sounded harsh to you that you 
edited out? 
 
A: Pardon me? 
 
Q: Can you tell me any of the sentences or the tone-- 
 
A: No, I can't remember. 
 
Q: Or the words that you edited out? 
 
A: No, I can't remember.  But the way it ended up going to her is 
exactly the way I wanted it. 
 
Q: After Taft reviewed the letter, did you get a chance to see it 
before you signed it? 
 
A: I believe so. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: You are not going to let me ask him about 
Exhibit 51, Mr. Baker? 
 
MR. BAKER: That's correct. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: We don't have to make any further record on 
that? 
 
MR. BAKER: I don't think so. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Okay. 
 
Q: After you got the letter from Taft, did you read it? 
 
A: I believe so, yes. 
 
Q: Did you make any further changes to it? 
 
A: I might have. 
 
Q: You will notice that the version from Taft sent to you is 
different from the one you signed. The one you signed, by the way, 
is Exhibit 52. Is that correct? 
 
A: Yes. : You see your signature there? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And the one that Taft sent you dated May 31 is one paragraph, 
whereas the final version is three paragraphs. Right? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Did you add those other two paragraphs? 
 
MR. BAKER: Well-- 
 
THE WITNESS: I don't know. 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
Q: Excuse me? You don't know? 
 
MR. BAKER: Unless you added them without any advice from 
any lawyer. You can answer that question. 
 
THE WITNESS: Can I read it? 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
Q: Yeah. What I want to know is whether you dictated in effect the 
last two paragraphs of the final version, which is Exhibit 52. 
(Witness reviews document.) 
 
A: Uh-huh. 
 
Q: And the question was whether you dictated the last two 
paragraphs. 
 
A: I believe so, yes. 
 
Q: Now, in this letter you didn't say anything about Gigi, did you? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Although, as you just testified, the Gigi incident had already 
occurred. Right? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Now, let me ask you: This letter also, this Exhibit 52 that you 
signed and addressed to Nicole, was messengered to her. Do you 
see that. 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: It says "via Messenger." 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Did she call you after she got this? 
 
A: No.  
Q:  Did she talk to you at all about it?  
A: No. 
 
Q:  Never?  
A: Never. 
 
Q: Is that correct, that she never talked to you? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Did you ever hear from anyone else about Nicole's receipt of 
this letter and reaction to it? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: So when you sent this letter, that was the last that you had to do 
with this whole subject matter. Right? 
 
A: That's correct. 
 
Q: Do you know whether she did what you requested in the letter? 
 
A: What do you mean? 
 
Q: Did she change her--the address of her primary residence? Do 
you know? 
 
A: I believe that her mail during that period of time stopped 
coming to my house, yes. 
 
Q: This is a very serious sounding letter. 
 
MR. BAKER: Don't answer that. 
 
Q: Do you agree with that? 
 
MR. BAKER: Don't answer that. Your characterization doesn't 
make it so. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: I am asking if he agrees with it. I didn't say it 
had to be so. He could say, "No, it's not. It's a frivolous tone." 
 
MR. BAKER: It has a sense of levity to it. Anything that discusses 
the IRS always has some levity to it. 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
Q: You wrote this letter because you wanted to frighten Nicole, 
didn't you? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: You were upset with her and you were retaliating against her, 
and that was your purpose in writing this. Right? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: And you knew that she didn't want to pay taxes, and you knew 
this would frighten her. Correct? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Threatening IRS action-- 
 
MR. BAKER: Don't hold that in front of the video-- 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: I didn't realize that I was going in front of the 
video. Was that in front of the video? 
 
MR. BAKER: The answer was yes. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Thank you for pointing that out, Mr. Baker. 
 
Q: You may answer. 
 
THE WITNESS: What's his last question? 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
Q: Do you think it was threatening? 
 
A: I don't think it's threatening at all. 
 
Q: How many times had you written Nicole in 1994 a letter that 
you had messengered to her house? 
 
A: Many times. 
 
Q: What were the subject matters of those letters? 
 
A: My schedule, the kids, some -- whatever might have been 
happening at the time. 
 
Q: Letters that you had signed. Addressed to her, Nicole Brown 
Simpson? 
 
MR. BAKER: Wait a minute-- 
 
Q: Well, I want to make sure were not talking about different 
things here. I am talking about a letter like this letter, where it's 
addressed to Nicole Brown Simpson by OJ. Simpson. sort of an 
official-sounding letter. 
 
MR. BAKER: Well, don't answer that. 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
Q: Did you ever write any letter like that? 
 
MR. BAKER: Don't answer the question. 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
Q: What were the letters you wrote to Nicole in 1994? 
 
A: Well, in '93 and '4--I'm trying to focus on '4. 
 
Q: Yeah, on '4. 
 
A: Probably more to do with my scheduling and stuff. My 
scheduling of things. 
 
Q: What kind of letters would you write about your scheduling? 
 
A: That if she was planning anything, this is my schedule. Cathy 
would send those letters. Or whatever was going on with the kids 
or something that I may have been planning to do or not planning 
to do, Cathy would dictate it and send it to Nicole. 
 
Q: The subject matter of those letters were children and family 
matters. Right? 
 
A: Scheduling, children, family matters, yes. 
 
Q: How many business letters did you write Nicole in the year 
1994? 
 
A: This is--I don't consider this a business letter. 
 
Q: You don't? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: How many letters about the subject of money did you send 
Nicole in 1 994? 
 
A: Maybe one or two. 
 
Q: What other ones do you remember? 
 
A: Pertaining to this in the beginning of the year when she was 
doing all of these things with her house and stuff. 
 
Q: What did you write to her? 
 
A: Just pertaining to this, you know. I gave her my advice. 
 
Q: In writing? 
 
A: Once or twice in writing, yes. 
 
Q: Typed up? 
 
A: Cathy would have typed it up, sure. 
 
Q: Did you have your lawyer review it? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: How many letters did you send to Nicole in 1994 that your 
lawyer reviewed? 
 
A: In '94, I can't recall. 
 
Q: Your lawyer reviewed the letter of June 6. Right? 
 
A: Yes. This letter was mainly intended for the IRS if they ever 
came after me. 
 
Q: So to the best of your knowledge, the letter of June 6, Exhibit 
52, is the only letter you sent Nicole in 1994 that your lawyer 
reviewed. Correct? 
 
A: To the best of my knowledge, yes. 
 
Q: Do you still have copies of those other letters that you said you 
sent, the scheduling letters, family letters? 
 
A: I never kept copies of any of them 
 
Q: Cathy would have them? 
 
A: --except this. 
 
MR. BAKER: Let him finish, please. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Sorry, Mr. Baker. 
 
MR. BAKER: Go ahead, OJ. 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
Q: Now let me show you--Would Cathy have copies of those 
letters? 
 
A: I don't know. 
 
Q: Did she destroy them? 
 
A: This one she should have kept a copy of. 
 
Q: Did she destroy any letters? 
 
A: Oh, I don't know. 
 
Q: Exhibit 53, do you see that? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And you have a copy right there. Mr. Simpson. 
 
 A: Yes. 
 
MR. KELLY: So what is 53? 
 
MR. BAKER: June 8. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: June 8 from OJ. Simpson to 15 Nicole Brown 
Simpson. 
 
Q: You dictated this letter to Cathy? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: What was the purpose of writing this letter? 
 
A: To basically have Nicole take some heat off Gigi. 
 
Q: What had Nicole done to Gigi on May 21 and 22 that prompted 
this letter? 
 
A: She came over and yelled at her for not being at my home on 
that weekend, at least that Saturday. 
 
Q: Have you ever written a letter like this one to Nicole before? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Where you admonished her not to do certain things? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: How many times? 
 
A: Two or three times. 
 
Q: In 1994? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: When was the last time before 1 994? 
 
A: I would believe probably in 1993. 
 
Q: What was the subject matter of the last letter that you remember 
in 1993? 
 
A: I don't recall. 
 
Q: During this time frame, at least from June 6 to June 8 or 
thereabouts, were you having a conflict in your relationship with 
Nicole? 
 
A: I was avoiding Nicole, but these letters were dictated long 
before this. 
 
Q: When were they dictated? 
 
A: As I told you, that week in May. 
 
Q: Why did they go out weeks later? 
 
A: Because Cathy evidently was busy or not in the office or--and I 
wasn't around. I was in and out of town. 
 
Q: Why did-- 
 
A: They didn't go out weeks later, incidentally. I'm sorry. 
 
Q: Why is that? 
 
A: Because I told them not to send this one. 
 
Q: You told who not to send what letter? 
 
A: Cathy not to send the June 8th letter, 
 
Q: You never sent it? 
 
 A: Never sent it. 
 
Q: You dictated it when? 
 
A: Sometime in that week in May. 
 
Q: And Cathy didn't--Cathy, when she takes dictation from you, 
she takes it in hand, you said. Right? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Then she goes to her typewriter and types it. Right? 
 
A: Sometimes, yes. It depends on what time of the day I told her. 
 
Q: Did Cathy type this letter on June 8 to the best of your 
knowledge? 
 
A: I would guess so, if that's what it says. 
 
Q: When did you tell Cathy-- 
 
A: That's when I got it. 
 
Q: Excuse me? 
 
A: That's when I saw it. 
 
Q: When Cathy got around to typing the letter and showed it to 
you, you said "Don't send it." Right? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: But you did send the letter of June 6 that you signed. Right? 
 
A: I hoped it would suffice. 
 
Q: Exhibit 52. Right? 
 
A: That's correct. 
 
Q: Do these letters refresh your memory, Mr. Simpson, that in June 
of 1994 you were upset and angry with Nicole? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Angry toward her? 
 
A: I wasn't angry towards her. 
 
Q: Trying to separate yourself from her? 
 
A: I was trying to keep some distance from her, yes. 
 
Q: And was she resisting that? 
 
A: She came by my house a few times. So I wouldn't call it really 
resisting, but, you know, it wasn't easy staying away from her. 
 
Q: What did you say in that first letter that Skip Taft thought was 
vengeful? 
 
A: I don't think I said anything that he thought was vengeful. 
 
Q: Why did he say that? 
 
MR. BAKER: Well, don't answer that question. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Wait a second. 
 
Q: You wrote something in that letter which your lawyer said 
sounded vengeful. Now, without telling me what you and your 
lawyer talked about, because your lawyer here won't let me, tell me 
what you said in that letter that was vengeful. 
 
MR. BAKER: Don't-- 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: You may answer. 
 
MR. BAKER: Yeah, wait. Your interpretation of this is totally 
different than mine. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Mr. Baker-- 
 
MR. BAKER: I am going to instruct him not to answer-- 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: The simple answer is that he can answer the 
question, and you don't need Mr. Baker's able assistance-- 
 
MR. BAKER: I need all the help I can get. I'm not that smart, and I 
need all the help I can get, but you're making the assumption here 
that he took out changes that were somehow vengeful, and that 
doesn't say that, even though you want to get into this document. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Mr. Baker, something prompted Mr. Taft to 
use the word "revengeful" of every single word in the English 
language. Now, I want to know what Mr. Simpson wrote or said--
wrote in his early l draft that prompted that word. 
 
MR. BAKER: You know, your interpretation is totally different, 
and you're right into the attorney-client privilege in my opinion, 
and I am not going to let him answer it. It's that simple. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: You know, a judge once told me that you 
were a tough hombre. Now I know why. 
 
MR. BAKER: I'm not tough. I have been so nice--you know, 
because it's you, I have been so nice, it's unbelievable. I'm usually 
relatively harsh. Aren't I, Michael? And I've been an absolute 
modicum of decorum in this deposition. 
 
MR. BREWER: I'm glad it's being preserved on videotape, 
because no one would ever believe it. 
 
MR. BAKER: I am, too. Thank you very much. How far are we 
going to go today? Just because I'm tired. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Well, Mr. Baker, I will ask a few more 
questions and we will adjourn, and we can resume at 9:30. 
 
MR. BAKER: Fine, anything you want. I am just asking a 
question, but that's fine. I appreciate that. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: I don't want you to be tired. I want you to be 
on your toes. 
 
MR. BAKER: That's why I love this business. I really do love the 
interchange with lawyers. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Plus you told me earlier today that I'm much 
better in the morning.  
 
MR. BAKER: I'm not going to give away my secrets anymore. 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
Q: Mr. Simpson, you can't remember anything you initially wrote 
that was revengeful, in your opinion? 
 
A: No. I know I wouldn't want to be revengeful, and I know I 
wouldn't want a letter to go to her revengeful, and I think the letter 
that went to her reflects exactly the way I felt, and obviously the 
changes or whatever that were done to it reflected exactly what I 
wanted, which this covering letter mentions. 
 
Q: Did you talk to Judy Brown during the last 30 days of--
Withdrawn. I want to focus on the period when you ended the 
relationship with Nicole-- 
 
A: Uh-huh. 
 
Q: --I guess it was around May 9, and when Nicole died on June 
12. 
 
A: Uh-huh. 
 
Q: Did you talk to Judy Brown during that time period about 
Nicole? 
 
A: Starting when? 
 
Q: That last 30 days. 
 
A: Yes, I believe so. 
 
Q: When did you last talk to Judy about Nicole? 
 
A: I'm guessing. I would say right when we split up. 
 
Q: To tell her that you were splitting up? 
 
A: No. To tell her about all my concerns about Nicole. 
 
Q: What did you tell Judy? 
 
A: Just the way she had been acting. I tried not to tell her about 
some other things that had happened, like the January incident and 
stuff, her drinking, the people she was hanging around with, 
because I tried in the year that we were together not to really get 
into that, but I had time and time again tried to alert Lou and Judy 
that when we all were together, to watch how much she drinks, and 
essentially that was the conversation, and the fact that I, you know-
-they were family to me, and she was Nicole's mother. Whenever I 
was concerned about Nicole, I'd call her mother. 
 
Q: After than that conversation, did you have any other 
conversations with Judy? 
 
A: I don't recall having any other conversations with Judy, no. We 
may have said "hi" or something at some point in time. 
 
Q: That was about it? 
 
A: That was about it. 
 
Q: After you told her about the reasons for your splitting up. 
Right? 
 
A: More my concerns. It was just more my concerns. We didn't 
talk much about having split up. I kinda wanted Nicole to go to 
therapy, and I talked about the therapy she had gone to before and 
how it appeared to have had a positive effect and how I tried to 
encourage her to do it again. and I would kind of stick by her 
through that. 
 
Q: Did you say to anybody, including Judy Brown, during this 
time period that, "If I find Nicole with another man, and I know 
she's seen with other men, I'll kill her"? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: "If I find her with another man, she'd better stay monogamous 
to me until August when I leave and keep up the image"? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Did you have any kind of arrangement with Nicole about the 
two of you until August? Does that ring a bell? 
 
A: I told her at one point at this time that when I told her I couldn't 
do this anymore, that if she went to therapy, I'd stay with it until I 
go back to New York. So we can try it through the summer until I 
go to New York, if she goes to therapy. 
 
Q: You mean when you decided to end the relationship, you left 
this opening? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: You said, "If you go to therapy, I'll keep an open mind"? 
 
A: No. I said--when I told her that I couldn't do it anymore, I said 
but if she would go to therapy, I would stay in the relationship until 
I go back to Buffalo--until I go back to New York. 
 
Q: What did she say? 
 
A: She didn't want to go to therapy. She didn't think it helped. 
 
Q: Then it was agreed upon and decided that that was the end. 
Right? 
 
A: I told her that was my condition: If she don't go to therapy, I 
wasn't going to do it anymore. 
 
Q: And that was it. 
 
A: That was it. 
 
Q: When you met Paula at the airport, did you say you surprised 
her? 
 
A: Yeah. 
 
Q: She didn't know you were coming in? 
 
A: Yeah. Well, I don't think she knew anything.  You know, part of 
me thinks Cathy may have told her, but she acted surprised, and I 
told Cathy-- 
 
Q: How did you know whether she might not have another man 
with her? 
 
A: Cathy told me that, as I told you already. Cathy told me that. 
 
Q: What did Cathy tell you? 
 
A: That she wasn't dating anyone. 
 
Q: But when you went to the airport to see Paula, you did not 
know for a fact whether she might be picked up by another man. 
Right? 
 
A: Yeah. No. I knew then that a limo was supposed to pick her up. 
I just didn't know if she was with somebody. 
 
Q: So you waited and saw that she wasn't? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: How did you see that? 
 
A: With my two eyes. 
 
Q: When she came off the plane? 
 
A: Yeah. She walked alone, and that's when I snuck up behind her. 
 
Q: Where? 
 
A: In the airport, in the terminal. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Okay, we will resume tomorrow. 
 
MR. BAKER: All right. Thank you, sir. 
 
THE VIDEOGRAPHER: This concludes the deposition of 
Orenthal James Simpson, Volume IV: The number of video tapes 
used was three.  We are going off the record, and the time is 
approximately 5:03. 
 
(ENDING TIME: 5:03 P.M.) 
 
I DECLARE UNDER PENALTY OF PERJURY THAT THE 
FOREGOING IS TRUE AND CORRECT'. SUBSCRIBED AT 
CALIFORNIA, THIS 25 DAY OF 1996  
ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON 
